surface: Speckled black/grey stone with pink tinges; face around Matrix 2 much blackened - esp. up to 5mm from edge of matrix; odd two patches of darkening only around matrix 1; ends and sides also with some darkening. Crack in stone across one side; occasional chip out of edge, especially at top of mould beside respective mouth-mouldings; inside of two matrix 1 loops very battered - that of Matrix 2 only a little; ribs, scorings of M.2 still quite crisp; ribs seem worn on M.1; flaw in stone on lower blade of matrix 2.
description: Dimensions: Length: Matrix 1: 13.7mm; Matrix 2: 107mm,Width: blade Matrix 1: 47mm; blade Matrix 2 41mm; Width mouth Matrix 1: 47mm; Width mouth Matrix 2: 52mm; Width axe face beneath moulding Matrix 1: 32.5mm; Width axe face beneath moulding Matrix 2: 34mm; Width body below loop Matrix 1: 38.5mm; Width body below loop Matrix 2: 42.5mm,Depth moulding Matrix 1: 9.5mm; Depth moulding Matrix 2: 8.5mm,Length ribs Matrix 1: 59mm (below base of moulding); Length ribs Matrix 2 53mm (below base of moulding),Depth matrix at moulding Matrix 1: 22mm; Depth matrix at moulding Matrix 2: 20.5mm,Wedge-shaped block, opposite faces converging; ends flat and also not quite parallel; sides bowed, thin end: two grooves off long edge with smaller notch in between, v. slight groove off either side?; thick end: central groove, other diffuse notches flanking - poss. damage; Matrix 1: marked ledge below slightly splayed moulding; rectangular body section with rib-emphasised corners; 3 straight slightly converging ribs; two loops - one springing from moulding, other from just below; spatulate blade forms towards edge; loop grooves with neat 'V' section; one corner rib continues straight where body expands; ribs 'V' sectioned. Matrix 2: upside down from Matrix 1; ledge under slightly splayed moulding; bowed rectangular body section - sides more splayed; rib-emphasised, or crisp body corners; three parallel ribs, not evenly spaced; loop groove with near 'V' section, springing from just below moulding; body parallel sided for much of axe; ribs 'V' sectioned, and tail away to nothing.
remarks: Thin sectioned - B.M. (Nat. HIst.),White ink inscr. "Mould in syenite - Lot 120, Soth. July 95, Duke Coll: found near Bulford, Amesbury, P:1173",SN 9 Mar. 78,PI(O),Submitted by P. Saunders for sectioning and recording 2.2.78.

collection: Bronze palstave discovered at Burton Green, a village on high ground 2 1/2 miles North West of Kenilworth, shortly before the 1914-18 war. It has remained ever since in the possession of its finder, Mr. W. A. Beamish, a builder of Hampton-in-Arden, but has been on exhibition at the Birmingham Art Gallery 1928-34 and 1934-36 at the Coventry Museum.
site: England, warwickshire,burton green,w.kenilworth
composition: Copper (81%),Tin (11%),Lead(0.9%),Zinc (2.7%),Iron and aluminum present but not determined. Not assayed, arsenic, antimony, phosphorus.
remarks: N.B.: These particulars enclosed in a letter dated 25th Sept. 1944, from Mr. W. A. Seaby, Keeper of the City Museum and Art Gallery, Birmingham, to the Secretary Smith of [...] London. In this letter it is states that the palstave is being published by Professor H.F. Humphreys, FSA in the Transactions of the Birmingham Archeological Society for 1941-1942.

collection: Neward-on-Trent Municipal Museum,Accession no. 788-1,Presented to Museum by Dr. Stallard, Burton Joyce.
site: England,Nottinghamshire,Burton Joyce,River Trent,Dredged from the River Trent near Burton Joyce in 1925.
surface: Smooth, unpitted, with very little corrosion, apart from incrustation mentioned above. Metal shows clearly.
other: Length: 6 7/8" = 174.625mm,Width: 1 3/16" at widest point = 30.1625mm,Thickness: 3/4" (19.05mm) at haft and tapering to 1/16" (1.5875mm) at point.,Weight: 3 oz. = 85.0486 gms
description: Small, socketed spear head, the socket being hollow to a distance of 4 1/2" from haft end, and continued as a solid rib along the remainder of the blade. There are side loops about 1 1/8" from haft end, but the holes of these loops now blocked with, hard rusty, incrustation, which also occurs in patches on one face of the blade, and just inside the socket. The sides of the socket below the blade have been slightly flattened by filing - the marks of which show clearly. The base of the socket is slightly indented all round. Edges of blade badly chipped and blade also slightly cracked.
publications: Unpublished
remarks: Compiled Sept. 1957 1/2, F. Waters.,Arthur Driver, Curator
